By Lemma \ref{finitespectrum}, the set $P_1$ is infinite. Suppose for the sake of contradiction, that none of the height-zero primes of $R$ fulfils the condition from the statement, i.e.\ for each $q \in P_0$, the set $T_q = P_1 \cap \overline{P_0 \setminus \{q\}}$ is finite. This implies that $\{q\} = {\operatorname{Spec}(R)} \setminus \overline{T_q \cup (P_0 \setminus \{q\})}$ is an open set, and clearly a principal one. Therefore, there is $t_q \in R$ such that for each $p \in {\operatorname{Spec}(R)}$, $t_q \in p$ iff $p \neq q$. However, the ideal $I = \sum_{q \in P_0} t_q R$ is contained in each height-one prime, but in no height-zero prime, implying that there are inifinitely many minimal primes over $I$, a contradiction.

For the final claim, it suffices to put $W = {\operatorname{Spec}(R)} \setminus \overline{P_0 \setminus \{q\}}$.
